    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_13">• A vector is a directed segment with start and end points.
\n • Its length is the distance between those points.
\n • Vectors can be equal, opposite, or null.</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_13">• Vectors add by triangle or parallelogram rule.
\n • Addition is associative and commutative.
\n • Subtraction uses the opposite of a vector.</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_13">• Parallelogram shows commutativity of vector addition.
\n • Vector subtraction equals the vector from end of b to end of a.
\n • Demonstrates geometric vector rules.</string>

    <string name="SectionOneQuiz_13">!!! Solve the Quiz !!!</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDef_13">• Multiplying a vector by x changes its length.
\n • Direction stays the same for x&gt;0 and reverses for x&lt;0.
\n • Defines scaling of a vector.</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryProperties_13">• Vector multiplication follows associative and distributive laws.
\n • Two vectors are collinear if one is a scalar multiple of the other.
\n • Expresses alignment through scalar ratios.</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExamples_13">• Using vector algebra, medians meet at one point.
\n • The centroid divides each median in a 2:1 ratio.
\n • Proof uses addition and multiplication of vectors.</string>

